Overview

This IP Margin Calculator is intended to help guide the determination of pricing intellectual property shared among Firms in accordance with the IP Framework using one of the two arm’s length models:

  • Resellers Margin
  • Cost Recovery

Upon completion of each calculation, the user can produce a PDF report as support for the calculation.

The IP Margin Calculator should be used according to the best judgement of the Member Firms. Should questions arise, please contact one of the following Network Tax individuals:

  • John Doe at email@email.com
  • Jane Smith at email@email.com

IP Resellers Margin Calculator

For more information on the Resellers Margin benchmarks, please click here.





Value: %

Reseller margins between 25% and 60% are supportable by a global benchmarking study on file with Network Tax.

The agreed point within this range should reflect the relative contribution of each territory, such as the sales, delivery and support activities undertaken, the assets and IP contributed and the risks assumed.

A higher reseller margin is appropriate, for example, where the reselling territory performs a larger share of relevant activities, such as:

  • Significant sales activities
  • Localization or customization
  • Client implementation
  • Customer support
  • Hosting and maintenance

Conversely, a lower reseller margin is appropriate when most of these activities are performed by the IP owning territory.

The application of the reseller’s margin as described above would apply where one or more of the aforementioned reseller functions are bundled into the fee that the reseller is charging the client. If the reseller is performing and charging the client separately for one or more of the aforementioned activities, it would be expected that the reseller would retain a reseller margin towards the lower end of the range.

Results

Resellers Margin

For IP that is licensed externally to clients, the “reseller’s margin model” may be used to determine the license fee to be charged when firms share such IP with one another. Under this model, the license fee due the IP Owner is determined by discounting the suggested retail price by a reasonably anticipated (arm’s length) margin. Application of the resellers margin model requires that the firm to firm license fee is based solely on the suggested retail price in the market and is established prior to local sale in the market. This allows local member firms to operate in an entrepreneurial manner and absorb the benefits or burdens of over or under pricing the IP when reselling in their local market.

Cost Recovery: Straight-Line

The cost recovery model may be used for the purpose of determining the license fee to be charged by one firm to another for use of IP. The intent of this model is to ensure that all participants pay an amount that reflects the benefits received. Conceptually, the intention is to (retroactively) reflect the conditions of a third party cost share arrangement. The license fee may be determined based on cost recovery proportionate to a reasonable allocation key for those territories expected to take a license, plus an additional fixed profit mark up (within an agreed upon range). The license fee may be (a) amortized over the anticipated life of the asset or (b) paid on a per unit basis.

Cost Recovery: Per Unit

The cost recovery model may be used for the purpose of determining the license fee to be charged by one firm to another for use of IP. The intent of this model is to ensure that all participants pay an amount that reflects the benefits received.
